<span id="v.iv.vi.xiv-p14"></span> It is better that we should give the
original of this sentence.  Its structure is characteristically
difficult, although the general sense, as Oehler suggests, is clear
enough:  “Quia vera quidem, sed non ex semine de statu simili (similis,
*Latinius* and *Junius* and *Semler*), sed vera de censu non vero
dissimili (dissimilis, *the older reading* and *Semler’s*).” We add the
note of Fr. Junius: “The meaning is, that Christ’s flesh is true indeed,
in what they call the identity of its *substance*, although not of its
*origin* (ortus) and *qualities*—not of its original, because not of a
(father’s) seed, as in the case of ourselves; not of qualities, because
these have not in Him the like condition which they have in us.”

